Calves were still sore today.  It was hot.  Felt tired and slow.
title: On UF campus

description: I actually felt fast during parts of the run.  My calves are sore but other parts of my lower legs (top of foot, ankle) seem to be ok.  It helps to go into a minimalist run starting fresh and without existing lower leg aches, tiredness, and stiffness.  I think my Nikes are still more forgiving on bad technique and tired legs.  My cardio is finally good enough where I can hold the tempo and technique (and keep "lifting") long enough to finish one of these runs in minimalist footwear.
title: Morning run in Bikilas... my longest run in VFF and my fastest pace yet in dailymile

description: I wanted to go exploring and find some new trails close to home.  It turns out that the nature trails at this city park are very short.  However, there are lots of places to run nearby including Devil's Millhopper so I managed to get over 5 miles in.  It was HOT and this was my first run carrying a water bottle.

Ran my usual Hogtown Greeway run.  Despite the trails being damp and the boardwalks still having some standing water, the concrete sidewalk parts did not chew up my feet.  Only took a tiny bit of skin off my right foot ball/toe area.  I guess my technique is getting better.

I liked that there were both gradual ups and downs as well as some pretty steep hills.  Felt pretty good considering this was my second run of the day.

title: 10 miles barefoot - San Felasco mountain bike trails
description: It is a lot of fun running barefoot on trails! This was a huge milestone for me.  Thanks Cathy B. for going slower today which allowed me to do this run.  Calves were still sore and tired from yesterday's 5k race. No major injuries from trail debris or tree roots. I had to remove a tiny thorn from my heel and I hit a rock or something that really hurt for a while. It was very hard to keep up the cadence and lift towards the end, so I was landing heavier on my whole foot than I wanted.  The feet and calves are sore.  My knees feel great, though.

title: Long barefoot trail run at San Felasco (Millhopper Rd)
description: Beautiful sunrise this morning. Some people never see those. Ran 4 x Hammock Cutoff loop so had lots of hills.  The last loop was really tough physically and mentally, had trouble picking up the legs. Matt C. was supposed to come out but bailed due to fear of muddy trails.  Larabar + NUUN worked great. I ate two bars total and had two water bottles with NUUN spaced out over the run and never felt any stomach discomfort.  Started getting a knot/cramp in my quad during lap 2 (before Larabar and NUUN). Fueled up for lap 3 and the knot went away.  I think this is my longest run ever in my whole life (even going back to college XC days) and I did it barefoot.  Tired but happy, I feel prepared for what comes next.

title: Brywood to 13th St
description: Feet still hurting from yesterday's race but I had to try out my new trail running shoes!  Only ran on sidewalks since it was dark, but the Adidas Kanadia 3 shoes lend themselves nicely to a midfoot strike. They are stiff and heavy but they let my feet land the right way. The Adidas Kanadia are on sale at Sports Authority for $50, and they have clearance section in the back with Kanadia 2 from last year in less boring colors. I wanted to get new shoes since my feet have expanded too much for my Nike Frees and the Frees just have too much heel lift.  I could not wait for all of the new minimalist shoes coming out in spring 2011.
Ankles were starting to get tight so I decided to go for a run.  Lots of kinks and creaks and sore tissue below the knees.

I left him (as we agreed) and then I started to push it. I was able to pick off runners the whole way back. Developed a knot in my right quad muscle.  Started pumping the gatorade at every aid station, the quad didn't end up being an issue.  Felt like I finished fairly strong.  The new shoes (MWU3) did fine.

Should have probably only gone 4 miles, but it is hard to stop once I go to all the trouble of getting on my gear and making it sweaty.  Muscles remembered at mile 6 that they were still microtorn/whatever from the recent half marathon.

title: San Felasco outer loop
San Felasco Yellow loop
description: Switched to MWU3... night and day compared to the Adidas Kanadias.  This loop felt much better.  Total for the day was 17.8 miles.
Pretty spent by the time I started this.  Managed to finish, making today my new longest running day with 17.8 miles total.
title: San Felasco Blue loop
2 mile personal time trial
description: My dad brought some old video tape from my college cross country days... watched to see my running form from way back then.  Inspired me to go run a little faster.

title: Glen Springs Rd. Loop
description: Have some nagging sorenesses but feels good to run fast.  I think the slight slope of the sidewalks is affecting my hips... I need to remember to go counter-clockwise on my loop routes for a few weeks.
Barefoot.
title: The Daily
First run back after being sick
description: My sinus issue will drag on for the next few weeks, but overall feeling good enough to run again.  All of my joints and connective tissue were very glad to have a week off anyway.

title: San Felasco outer loop
description: Nice run with Matt C.  Rain was COLD.
It was cold at 5am but at least there was very little wind.  Base layers people, base layers.

title: loop near West Side Park
description: Using the new POSE-inspired form that my Physical Therapist wants me to try.  It apparently did not make me slower.

title: Warm enough to run barefoot!
description: It seems best for me to work on form issues without shoes on.  Pushing the hips forward / out plus keeping my trailing foot closer to the ground (instead of coming up so far under my butt) seems to be working... my front foot lands more under me than in front of me and it is way easier to maintain 180 cadence.  It also makes it hard to run slow.  :)   It *will* be nice when the sidewalks are free of acorns, nut shells, and other fall debris.
VFF and Barefoot.  The Bikilas continue to want to rub a raw spot on the inside of my feet just above the arches... took them off and carried them before too much damage was done.
title: Harris Branch

description: Carrying my NB Minimus Road after taking them off in frustration.
title: barefoot last mile
xmas day run
description: Santa and family were good to me this year.  Received a bunch of running clothes and a stopwatch / heart rate monitor.  Had to try them out.

title: Zilker Holiday Tree 5k
description: Mile Splits: 6:46, 6:14, 7:07.  Lots of slow bodies ahead of me at the start. It also looks like I died just a bit.

title: shake out run
description: Trying to unwind the kinks from being in a car for 2 days.  My new heart rate monitor is really cool.

title: San Felasco outer loop
description: Beautiful day. The temperature warmed up very fast (it was over 70 degrees by the time I was finished).  I saw a bobcat in the wild!  I followed him down the trail for a while before he noticed me (probably 20 feet away).  First long run with the chest strap on the heart rate monitor.  Works great.  I'm still learning what I need to do to get the information out of it afterwards though.  Was gonna run longer today but my form started to deteriorate so I called it quits.
Concentrated on form.  When I get it right (like tonight) these runs are therapeutic for my Achilles tendon issue.
title: flat 8th ave
nice run in VFF
description: Rolled out of bed after a nap and hit the greenway  I feel like the strengthening work is paying off.  Tempo run in the middle felt fast and easy.

title: brisk San Felasco blue loop
description: Matt C. tweaked his ankle so we stopped and walked for some of this.  Even though it was COLD we saw a barefoot runner.
Not sure the time is right... still figuring out my new watch.  Fizzled hard on this one, probably due to my attempt at cutting back on food intake yesterday.
title: San Felasco hammock cutoff

description: Hot!
title: along Waldo Rd
8th Ave short flat
description: Tried out my new Injinji toes socks with my VFF.  I like. On my legs I wore a base layer plus running pants.  On top I wore some kind of wool blend base layer plus a fleece vest. Hat and gloves. There was no wind so this kept me plenty warm (but not hot!).  You folks still wearing cotton during extreme temperatures need to try synthetics or wool rather than the dreaded "death fabric".
Felt nice and smooth.  Glutes and hips were sore from the PT earlier in the week.  Core is still weak, hard to hold my hips in position for the entire run.  First 30 minutes was spot-on though.

title: neighborhoods
description: I was bad at dinner so this was to help burn off a huge pile of fish and chips (fried fish, onion rings, and french fries).  Decided to stay off concrete sidewalks and find some nice, quiet neighborhoods so I could run on the asphalt streets.

Needed to burn off the three varieties of beer soup I made yesterday, plus pancakes for breakfast today.  Running can be a thing of beauty... I had about 10 minutes of completely effortless running. Able to maintain proper form for a bit longer this time.  Would have had better pace overall if I hadn't bonked hard at the end... oh man my GLUTES!  Rainy but turned out to be a great day to run.  T-shirt and shorts were perfect.
title: 23rd Blvd to University
Now that I have learned how to run...
description: I thought I would give my Nike Free Run+ another try. Still burning off high-energy beer soups.  Didn't have any knee issues (which is why I quit running in my Frees). My ankles were happy to have some cushion I think, although it was hard to find my midfoot with the raised heel. I aggravated my Achilles a little bit (I was actually hoping the heel would help).  Also ended up with blisters on my big toes, even with socks, confirming that the toe box in the Frees is too narrow.  Will have a clean conscience when I buy new shoes next month. :)
The wet packed sand felt good under my VFF.  Going slow enough and short enough that I didn't get any rubbed raw spots.
title: easy greenway warmup for PT

description: I thought that since my feet were warmed up I'd be able to go sockless with the sandals.  My toes got cold rather quickly and the thin sandals did not insulate from the cold ground.  I hate cold toes.  Traction was not as good as the RunAmocs on wet boardwalk.  The good news is that again my forefoot to midfoot conversion seems to make these more comfortable to wear (not so much friction in between the toes).
title: Gave the huarache sandals another try
tweaked something
description: I guess the playground sprinting caught up with me today. Overall mileage was also a big jump over last week (since my Achilles is getting better).  Tweaked something in my upper hamstring or hip / glute area.  Walked a little and then was able to jog the last 1.5 miles home.   I need to watch those week-to-week mileage increases.
I'm liking my RunAmocs for easy runs.
title: greenway in mocs
Too gorgeous to wear shoes
description: Sunny and 70 degrees, could not bring myself to put on shoes.  Felt great except the feet are a little soft and tender from so many weeks without any barefoot work.
Nice to be running tonight.
title: 8th Ave short flat

description:
Don't like running in my Nike Frees anymore, but wanted the cushion for my chappy feet.  I long for a pair of Altra Running Instincts:
http://altrarunning.com/mens/instinct/
title: University Ave 6mi loop
The Armadillo Run at San Felasco
description: I saw five armadillos today, my all-time single-day high.  Stopped to look at a few of them so lost a little time there. Ran the outer loop (blue+yellow) with Sandhill Cutoff. That trail is nice, it is the first time I tried it... mostly grass and pine needles instead of the loose sand.  Shortens the route by .5 miles.  Still getting a little twitch in my right glute (from two weeks ago when I bumped up my mileage too much) and the blistery foot has a few places where the skin is dry/cracked.  It was nice to be on trails again, it feels like it has been a long time.

title: 8th Ave short flat
description: fartlek x 2.  The new hip position / posture is almost starting to feel natural.  Feet were in good enough shape to wear VFF.

title: one-third mile hill repeats
description: Seven uphill repeats with recovery in-between.  Splits:  2:08 / 2:03 / 2:01 / 2:00 / 2:01 / 1:56 / 1:55.  Recoveries ranged from 2:43 - 3:49.

Towards the end I lost all energy... I think my body decided it wanted to digest my huge Texas Roadhouse dinner.  I'm having a hard time believing the pace time, I *must* have screwed something up on my watch.  Normally I just let it run through the traffic light stops but tonight I tried marking my stops to get a more accurate time.  Guess it backfired... unless I am getting that much faster without realizing it.  Edit: yeah, screwed up the watch, corrected.
title: Texas Roadhouse Revenge

description: Got 2nd place overall!  Did ok following my race plan, but didn't feel completely great this morning.  Ended up chatting with the guy who won through most of the race.  It turns out that sub-7 minute mile pace is not "conversational pace" for me, especially when running up that hill by the fraternities... that's where the winner dropped me.
title: Cupid Fun Run 5k

description: I really like the hammock cutoff loop due to the concentration of hilly terrain.
title: San Felasco Hammock Cutoff - lap 1

description: Pushed the second lap a little bit more.
title: San Felasco Hammock Cutoff - lap 2

description: Longest run for me in a long time.  Hopefully increasing my distance this week without causing any injuries. Last week I ran hard (intensity increase) so this week will be all easy runs.  I swear it got colder during this run... the cold, dank fog came after me.  Fueled by large portions of Ropa Vieja and mojo rice plus the Valentine's Day cookies I should not have eaten right before bed.
Saw a *lot* of other runners out there today.
title: 8th Ave short flat

description: This is an out-and-back route.  Ran 19:05 out, 15:52 back.  Nice evening.  VFF felt good.
title: 8th Ave short flat

description: Felt pretty crummy the whole way, although turned part of it into a tempo run... it is hard not to speed up running past campus and the bars on University Ave.  I've been behind on sleep, stressed, and eating like crap.  I was under-veggied, under-fruited, over-meated, and over-junk-fooded this week.  I think my body and glutes noticed that I've been skipping my PT and core strengthening lately.  On the bright side, I think all of the push-ups etc. are paying off... I'm pretty sure I received a cat call from a car full of college girls.
title: long night loop

description: Stiff, sore, and creaky.  Airplane and car rides suck.  But good to be back home safe and sound.
title: First run since getting home from vacation
First run in NB Minimus Road
description: Too early to tell how these shoes will do for me.  I think I may have bought a half size too small.  My feet drifted up towards the toes a little bit, making the shoe feel smaller than when I tried it at the store.  I had to take off my thick socks.  Felt ok sockless.  The raised heel definitely affects my foot landing, we'll see if I can adjust. Better for me than Nike Free for sure, though.

title: Long run in RunAmocs
description: I have been re-reading the Lydiard, decided I needed to get in some 2-hour endurance-building runs.  Wanted to try doing a long run in my RunAmocs.  Ran on greenway / trails where I could, including Clear Lake Nature Area where I had never been before. RunAmocs worked fine.  Not exactly sure of the distance or pace.

title: Brywood hills
description: Just around my neighborhood.  A good week of running.  No injuries.  Looking forward to Trail of Payne next weekend.

Started out great running at cruise speed. Ended poorly.  Hamstrings were still sore from the weekend.  Developed twinges around my knees and achilles.  The raised heel on the NB Minimus is the most likely cause, it definitely affects my stride.  Finally gave up and barefooted it home.
title: nice weather
Long run in VFF
description: Took almost a whole week off after last weekend's race to see if my Achilles area would settle down.  The lack of activity actually seemed to have made it stiff and irritable, so it felt good to get out and run.  Hogtown Creek Greenway to Loblolly Woods, over to Green Acres Park, across the top of the levy to Clear Lake Nature Park, back up 8th Ave to Cofrin Nature Park, across 16th Ave and up through Alfred Ring Park, loop Glenn Springs Rd. to 34th St. and back home.  One bathroom break and two water stops, I didn't carry anything.  Ran to depletion.  A good LSD endurance run.

title: barefoot greenway and neighborhood
description: Except for the barf burp, felt nice.

title: San Felasco 4 x Hammock Cutoff loop
description: Supposed to be my easy day, but saw Dan C. and his group turn onto the trail a little way ahead of me. Decided to catch up and run with them for a while (hunter instinct?).  See if you can figure out which loop that was.... loop splits (3.8 miles each):  41:02 / 31:14 / 35:19 / 36:14.  Beautiful day in the Hammock.  Trails are in great shape due to recent rain and it looks like they cleaned them off for the planned maintenance burns.  Didn't have any noticeable smoke smell.  My overall time includes the jog to the car and back for refueling.  Continuous forward motion...

title: long night loop
description: I do not like that increasing intensity aggravates my Achilles tendon area.  I do like that my endurance training seems to be working.
Seems like any weeknight where I actually get to run with the sun still up leads to barefootin'.
title: barefoot

description: First run of the new year!  Making myself take it easy.
title: Happy 2013

description: Initial feeling is that I'll be keeping the Instincts.  They are not "minimalist" since they are very cushioned but they do support "natural" running motion.  No raised heel = no knee pain!  There is a loss of proprioception so I had to remind myself to "run light".  I am curious to see how they do on a long run.  I woke up REALLY stiff in my lower legs this morning.  Also have not been feeling great, eating junk (Easter candy has started to appear), and not enough FRUIT and VEGGIES!
title: First run in Altra Instincts
3 hours in Altra Instincts
description: I have found my new Long Day shoe - the Altra Instinct.  Shoes did great on sidewalk, road, and greenway / gentle nature trails.  Just guessing at the distance and pace.  I was trying to hit 3 hours of forward motion and I made it.  I have determined that it helps tremendously to injest calories on runs this long.

title: Blue Ridge mountain roads
description: Ran from our rental house in Blowing Rock on Appalachian Ski Mountain down to highway 321 and back.  There were some pretty steep sections.

title: Altra Instincts cure Achilles Tendinitis?
description: I cannot explain it but running in the Altra Instincts seem to be curing me of my Achilles pain.  This morning was my third run in them.  Nagging injury for the last six months is disappearing in a week since getting the new shoes.
It's da shoes!  Perfect cool evening for a fast pace run in my Altra Instincts.  Second part of a double run day.
title: Yeah!
long night loop
description: Still pretty warm and humid out there.  Felt tired.  Here are notables from earlier in the day... work was blah, ate a big lunch (Indian buffet), skipped my Workrave (lots of sitting today), steak was part of dinner.

title: San Felasco 2x outer loop with Dan C.
description: Faster than I've been going on my long easy days, but I was able to hang with it. Nice cool morning.  Altra Instincts are "Dan Stoner - Approved!" for San Felasco and Florida trails.

title: Run run run til the sun comes up...
description: Saw coyote or grey fox in Cofrin Nature Park.

Just felt terrible.  I'm sure the heat was a contributor.  Also notice some commonalities with the last time I felt bad running after work... I skipped my Workrave again, sitting in my chair all day.  So bad my back hurt getting up to go each lunch and again at the end of the day.  Sitting is baaaaad, mmm-kay?  Also had a huge Chipotle burrito for lunch. Need to eat smaller lunch and maybe have an afternoon snack instead of suffering the big bloat.  Oh yeah, and I didn't have afternoon coffee like usual.
title: totally awful
Happy Easter
description: Acclimate... acclimate... acclimate... Gotta get used to this heat.
So stiff and creaky this morning...

description: Thought I'd feel good after taking a couple of days off. At first I thought it was going to be a good run but instead I felt stiff in a lot of strange places, generally tired.  Maybe mental.
title: meh

description: Went easy except for when I ramped up to top speed for a stretch, feeling out whether I could do a serious race barefoot.  Tore my feet up a little.  Not ready for fast barefoot yet.
title: barefoot

description: Morning run.  Longest ever! Did my long greeway out-and-back twice and then tagged on some more at the end.  Even though I ate my homeade energy bars and drank fluids the whole way, I was really dead by the end and afterwards my weight was the lowest recorded this century.  Temperature probably went up 20 degrees from the beginning to the end.  Treated myself to Five Guys (hamburger and fries) for lunch.  Splits (actual running) for each out or back (4.4 miles each): 41:59 / 40:07 / 40:02 / 44:36.  Last 2.6 miles in 31:45.  About 12 minutes of jog to my house, refuel, and bathroom stops.  The 3 hours 31 minutes was total clock time.
title: no sidewalks

description: Felt really short compared to the 20-miler I ran on Sunday.
title: Brywood hills
one-third mile hill repeats
description: After running my hill loop I still felt good, so decided to do some hill repeats, full recovery in-between (HR back to 120).  Splits:  2:06 / 2:06 / 2:00 / 1:59.  This was WAY better than the last time I did hill repeats (about a month ago).  Feeling fit and loving the Altra Running shoes.

title: Hogtown Creek Greenway
description: Legs and feet were stiff. Very nice cool morning.
That's what I'm talking about. Cardio is in good shape. Form must have broken down towards the end, started feeling some twinges in both Achilles.
title: nice night

description: The cool ocean water felt better after going for a run on the beach.
title: barefoot on the beach
too... many... french fries
description: Really bad eating weekend.  Fish and Chips twice.  Hamburger and fries twice.  Ice cream at least three times.  A few beers. Started this run about 6 pounds heavy.  Time to get back on the healthy eating wagon.

title: run
description: It appears that my body is responding favorably to the speed work.  Started out at what felt like an "easy" pace and noticed I ran the first two miles at 8:30 pace. I guess I let my speed creep up from there.  I was pretty tired by the end, though. The biggest change I notice as a result of introducing hill intervals into my training is that I have more knee lift / power / drive in each stride.  If my legs recover I might run the 5k with the Duck on Saturday.

title: Run Amuck with the Duck
description: ** Edit:  Course was short. ** Huge PR and placed 2nd overall, despite a poorly-marked course and the fact that the race went off about a half hour late.  These people need to attend Race Director training.  I was pretty thirsty by the time we started and the air temperature only got hotter.  I stayed back from the leaders enough so I didn't make any wrong turns myself.  At least one poor guy went down flat trying to recover.  Very happy with my race performance.

title: barefoot walk / run
description: Time to get serious about developing my foot pads.

Felt cool this morning.  Did my "Brywood hills" and "no sidewalks" routes.  The trails were nice and soft from all of the rain.  The forests were happy.  Just drank water before and during, I was glad to get some coffee in me when I got home.
title: Recovery run

description: This was a great workout.  Did a variation on my Brywood hill loop twice.  Got winded going up the hills, pushed over the top, and tried to recover while maintaining brisk pace on the downside.  No intervals this week. Still feeling Saturday's race I think.  Sore in the glutes, hips, and calves.  Pains in my knees, ankles, feet, and Achilles.  Loop splits: 26:45 / 23:53.  A cool 55 degrees when I started.
title: Brywood hills
no sidewalks
description: Many non-running things going on over this past week.  It payed to ease back on the running during time of stress... had a good run this morning.

title: that... felt... weird
description: Started off feeling easy but then got light-headed.  Stopped to walk a few times.  Seemed disconnected from my body's signals.  I'm sure the heat played a role but overall just felt weird.

Tight in the ankles.  Achilles area tender.

description: Blah.

description: New shoes are the RunAmoc DASH Smooth by Soft Star Shoes.  Bought them to be my new daily work shoes but decided to give them a try running.  Great great improvements over the previous RunAmoc LITE.  Mine have the trail sole which makes them a bit heavy (probably heavier than my Altra Instincts).  A fun shoe.  Would make a great XC option for some people.
title: jog to the track in new RunAmoc DASH

description: Testing out the RunAmoc DASH Smooth on the track.  Four x 400m with jog 400 in between.  Splits: 1:20 / 1:21 / 1:20 / 1:19.

title: Freedom 8k Inaugural race in Green Cove Springs
description: It was pretty cool to be lined up at the starting line behind / beside elite runners.  Unfortunately, this pulled me along to a first mile that was faster than planned. The race was hot and painful and a big mental challenge.  Happy with the results.  First in my age group.  The course was very well-marked, a nice venue.

title: Brywood to NW 31st Blvd (Glen Springs Rd) out and back
description: Recovery run. Still sore and stiff from Monday's race.
Jog to Gainesville Health and Fitness and back home.
title: GHFC round trip

description: Wow bleh!  Creaky in the ankles and many muscles are still sore from Friday's Core workout at GHFC, especially the glutes.  Did some walking.  Feet feeling odd, wonder if my shoes are starting to break down (my Altra Instincts have 230 miles on them).
title: no sidewalks
VFF for the first time since April
description: Since my Altra Instincts feel like they are going flat I decided to switch back to my VFF for a change. At the beginning everything felt good.  It was nice to sense the ground again.  I could feel the built-in spring of the foot, lower leg and tendons.  But after about 30 minutes my Achilles started to ache. Towards the end I had some discomfort in the arch and around the toe pockets.  I'm a bit frustrated with shoes right now.  Probably need to start rotating footwear again anyway to help minimize repetitive motion injuries.
Still do not like NB Minimus Road.  However, they remind me that I need to "run light", something I was cheating on in my Altra Instincts.
title: GHFC round trip
no sidewalks
description: Lot's of blah runs lately.  Either this is my body telling me its time to take off a few weeks with complete rest due to longterm muscle fatigue (e.g. overtraining syndrome), or my central governor is pissed about the pain I suffered during my last race.  I'm sure the heat doesn't help.  Ran in my RunAmoc DASH, it's a nice shoe.

title: San Felasco 3x Hammock cutoff
description: Turned into a walkfest.  Not sure if it's in my head or if my body really needs a break.  I intend to take a few weeks off.  I have never in my life trained consistently for an entire year, it is reasonable that the body needs some complete rest.
The secret to barefoot running... bend your knees until you think you look funny, then bend them some more.
title: barefoot run on sidewalks

description: Bend the knees, bend the knees.  Run lightly.  The foot should kiss the ground like an airplane coming in for a landing.  Felt pretty good in my VFF although I had some rubbing around the toe pockets.  My body finally revolted against all that rest by giving me horrible heartburn / acid reflux last night. Prior to this, I hadn't had any noticeable heartburn over the whole last year since I started running.  I had to get out and move tonight to keep the stomach acid at bay.
title: run in the rain

description: Really stiff this morning and still some soreness from the last run a few days ago.  Ran a short stretch on the roughest road I have been able to locate (stones embedded in asphalt). Bending the knees I was able to handle this just fine.
title: barefoot morning run

description: I was inspired after learning that one of my new coworkers runs barefoot.  Included twice over my favorite coaching surface.  A little too soon after dinner... This run fueled by Adams Rib Co.
title: barefoot four
Melon Run 3 mile race - Barefoot
description: My first barefoot race on mostly paved surface. This course has about a half mile on greenway boardwalk / dirt trail, the rest was sidewalk and street.  Definitely went out a little too fast but held on for top-3 in my age group which earned me a watermelon!  My main goal was to race but keep my barefoot form and avoid blisters.  My feet are in good shape with just a few hot spots so I feel like I met my goal.

Calves were sore all week from the race.  They were better today before the run, but definitely sore again now!  The next skill for me to master is relaxing the calves.  I have no idea how to do this.  I think I'm done with my "rest" phase, ready to start doing some LSD endurance training.
title: long night loop
Brywood to NW 31st Blvd (Glen Springs Rd) out and back

description: Barefoot at night is ok.  All sidewalks.  My "curl up the toes" muscles were not strong enough to keep them up towards the end so I have some tender areas on my big toes, had to slow down to keep myself in the happy feet zone.

Wore two long sleeve shirts, running pants, socks and shoes to encourage heat acclimation. I have not been able to run in over a week (wife out of town) so it felt good to get out there.
title: Heat acclimation run

description: Wow, seems like a really long time since I ran on the trails of San Felasco.  Did Blue plus Yellow outer loop barefoot.  Even though I turned into a wet soggy mess, I never felt too hot.  The heat acclimation run (long sleeves and pants) seems to be working to make a normal run like today feel nice and cool.

description: I survived another heat acclimation run.
title: Glen Springs Rd. Loop

description: A nice morning for a barefoot run.

description: Had to walk a few times when the foot/ankle thing started hurting.
title: Brywood hills
no sidewalks
description: Part 2 of a double. My brain and body seemed to remember the "run light" pattern from this morning's barefoot run so I felt good in my cushioned Altra Instincts.  Still hot out there but the breeze helped.

Awesome difficult trail running in the Blue Ridge Mountains.  Got on the Tanawha Trail at the Cold Prong parking area and ran uphill to the boardwalk at Rough Ridge.  The trails were rooty and rocky and beautiful.  Didn't see another human except for the guy who convinced me (thank you!) to continue on up the trail to Rough Ridge.  The views of Grandfather Mountain and the surrounding area were spectacular.  Soft Star RunAmoc DASH with trail sole were awesome for this run.  The trail sole had plenty of protection from the roots and traction was great on the rounded boulders of the Appalachians.  According to my watch I was actually 10 minutes slower on the way down than the way up.  I did not run with GPS but according to this site I believe the elevation of my run ranged from 3600 feet - 4600 feet.  http://b-fick.com/gps/2008/tanawha-trail
title: Blue Ridge Mountains Tanawha Trail

description: Mid-day trail run.  Was planning to do a whole lot more but some muscles are still complaining about last week's mountain running. Sore muscles combined with the heat, I decided to call it quits.

barefoot night run
description: Included two passes over my "favorite" barefoot coaching surface (perhaps "terribly effective" is a better choice of words).

title: First run in Moc3

Closest to barefoot of any of my minimalist shoes (this includes huarache sandals and VFF Bikila).  Able to easily feel the ground and maintain my barefoot running form.  No cushion, just some protection.  Great forefoot shape and fit.  No silly toe pockets.  Happy with this shoe.

title: no sidewalks
description: I was a bit stiff and sore in the ankles at first, pretty typical of days when I roll out of bed and head out the door.  Wore my new Soft Star Moc3s again. Good stuff.

Round trip to from stadium and 8 x stadium stairs.  Had a nice rainshower about halfway through to cool me off.  I think I'm ready to declare my Altra Instincts officially dead.  Disappointing cushion durability, but right now I'm leaning towards buying another pair.
title: Stadium Stairs at the Swamp
long beautiful night run in Moc3
description: A nice cool night. My Moc3s were fine, this time I wore Injinji toe socks to prevent blisters between my toes.  Haven't run anything near this far since May.  I needed this.

Trying to correct some of my minor form issues that I noticed in the high speed video I received from the UF Ortho study.  The two big things were 1. I had asymmetric arm carriage 2. I had completely lost the "falling forward" pattern. I noticed while running tonight that falling forward encourages "popping" the feet back up off the ground more quickly. I remember that! But I had not been doing it. I wore my Altra Sampsons for the first time in a while. I think my previous Achilles complaints from these shoes stemmed from the fact that I was doing it wrong. description: A long day of trail running at San Felasco in the heat wearing my Merrell Vapor Gloves. I started the morning by exploring the hiking trails on the south side of Millhopper Road. Then I followed blue blaze trail to a service road, crossed the gate into the wilderness area, and ended up on horse trails on the north side of the park. Lots of mountain bikes out today. I wandered on curvy singletrack to the north parking area to refill my water bottles and cool down. I was hot and tired by this point (3 hours in and approaching noon), so I wanted to avoid the singletrack on the way back. I needed to get to the bridges near the Soggy Bottom / CreekSide loops to hop back on the horse trails and find that gate. Never did find my way. Next time I will take a map. After getting lost, using up all my food and gels, and almost running out of water, I decided to cross the wilderness swamp that I had used in years past (follow the powerlines). I didn't need to wade through anything more than ankle-deep water (whew!). I did a lot walking during that last hour. I was glad to arrive back at my car with cold water and food waiting for me. Today was a nice adventure (despite the biting flies and ticks), and I saw a couple of hawks, a big wise old owl, some deer (including a cute little fawn), and a large herd of feral pigs. Love the Vapor Gloves.
